x4freetext: The sector-focusing cyclotron in the
Heavy Ion Research Facility Lanzhou (HIRFL), China.
The typical average thickness of the natural 169Tm
targets was around 600 mu-g/cm2.
The thickness of 187Re targets
was in the range of 310 to 370 mu-g/cm2. The targets
were prepared by the high-vacuum evaporation
technique on Al backing of thickness around 1.0 mg/cm2.
Two Si(Au) surface-barrier detectors, the two
monitor detectors were used to detect the elastically
scattered particles from a Au foil placed upstream
from the targets.
A dedicated array consisting of 16 high-purity
Ge (HPGe) detectors coupled to a VME-based maximum
integrated data acquisition system. After the end of
each activation run, the target and its associated
catcher were placed in between two HPGe detectors
positioned 180. to each other. The distance between
the target and the detector was about 10 cm. The
crystal of the detector and the target-Al foils were
surrounded by a cylindrical Pb shield to reduce
scattered gamma rays from neighboring targets and
background from natural radioactivity.
Each type of target was grouped into two
stacks (each stack contains eight target-Al foils).
Energy loss was calculated by ATIMA within the LISE++
program.
A Faraday cup was installed downstream of the
scattering chamber to measure the beam current.
The activation technique with the
detection of offline gamma rays was used to derive
the cross sections. A stack of targets was used to
extract the excitation function using the energy
degradation technique.
The errors of the measured cross sections are
mainly from the statistical uncertainties.
